Very little, if you use it only for **JWT decoding inside your existing callback flow**.

Seeing a login screen means your current **OIDC redirect flow is already working**. Adding the Spring JWT jar does **not** need to change that flow unless you also enable Spring Security auto-protection on endpoints.

## Keep your existing flow

You should keep this flow exactly as it is:

1. `/auth/start`
2. redirect to Keycloak login
3. Keycloak redirects to `/auth/callback`
4. Arthur Core exchanges `code -> token`
5. Arthur Core parses JWT claims
6. Arthur Core calls Lancelot `getUserById(...)`
7. Arthur Core creates Redis session

So the JWT jar should be used only at **step 5**.

---

## What to add

Add this dependency:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-oauth2-resource-server</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

Then create a small service that uses `JwtDecoder`.

---

## What not to change

Do **not** switch your app to Spring Security login flow.
Do **not** replace your custom `/auth/start` and `/auth/callback`.
Do **not** enable default OAuth2 login config.

That would interfere with the flow you already built.

---

## Safest way to use the jar

Use it only as a library for decoding tokens.

### Jwt service

```java
@Service
public class JwtService {

    private final JwtDecoder jwtDecoder;

    public JwtService(JwtDecoder jwtDecoder) {
        this.jwtDecoder = jwtDecoder;
    }

    public JwtUserClaims extractClaims(String token) {
        Jwt jwt = jwtDecoder.decode(token);

        JwtUserClaims claims = new JwtUserClaims();
        claims.setSub(jwt.getSubject());
        claims.setPreferredUsername(jwt.getClaimAsString("preferred_username"));
        claims.setEmail(jwt.getClaimAsString("email"));
        claims.setGivenName(jwt.getClaimAsString("given_name"));
        claims.setFamilyName(jwt.getClaimAsString("family_name"));

        return claims;
    }
}
```

### Decoder bean

Use the **internal Keycloak URL**, not the browser hostname:

```java
@Configuration
public class JwtConfig {

    @Bean
    public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
        return JwtDecoders.fromIssuerLocation(
                "http://keycloak.ns-keycloak.svc.cluster.local/realms/arthur-local"
        );
    }
}
```

---

## Then only change your callback logic here

Right after token exchange succeeds:

```java
String idToken = (String) tokenResponse.get("id_token");
JwtUserClaims claims = jwtService.extractClaims(idToken);

String userId = claims.getSub(); // or username/email if Lancelot expects that
UserResponse user = lancelotClient.getUserById(userId);
```

That is the only real code-path change.

---

## Important warning

Adding this dependency can sometimes make Spring Security start protecting endpoints automatically if you already have security config on the classpath.

If that happens, your endpoints may suddenly require auth and break your current flow.

## To keep your existing flow, add a minimal security config

If you already use Spring Security or the new jar triggers it, define this:

```java
@Configuration
public class SecurityConfig {

    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            .csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())
            .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
                .requestMatchers("/auth/**").permitAll()
                .anyRequest().permitAll()
            );

        return http.build();
    }
}
```

This keeps your current endpoints open and avoids Spring trying to take over login.

